{{Infobox Halacha |image=[[File:Potzberg Eselfohlen.JPG|300px]] |caption= |verse={{bibleverse||Exodus|13:13|HE}} and {{bibleverse||Exodus|34:20|HE}} |talmud=[[Bekhorot]] 5b |mishnah= |rambam= |sa= }}
The '''Petter Chamor''' ({{lang-he|פטר חמור}}) or '''Redemption of the firstborn donkey''', is a [[mitzvah]] in [[Judaism]] in which a male firstborn ([[Firstborn (Judaism)|bechor]]) [[donkey]] is redeemed by the owner of the donkey, who gives a [[sheep|lamb]] or [[goat|kid]] to a [[Kohen]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishpress.com/pageroute.do/44853/ |title=Petter Chamor &ndash; Redeeming A Donkey |date=August 11, 2010 |accessdate=November 3, 2011 |last=Tannenbaum |first=Rabbi Gershon |work=[[The Jewish Press]] |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101228044820/http://www.jewishpress.com/pageroute.do/44853/ |archivedate=December 28, 2010 |df= }}</ref> The lamb is not required to be firstborn.
The mitzvah, albeit rare in modern times, is listed as an "obligation of the body" <ref>("chovath haguf" vs. "chovath hakarka" -an obligation required solely on one of the [[land of Israel]])</ref> and thus mandatory for diasporic Jewry.
{{multiple image | align = left | direction = horizontal | header = | image1 = פדיון פטר חמר.jpg | width1 = {{#expr: (190 * 800 / 203 ) round 0}} | caption1 = Men's section of a Petter Chamor in [[Toronto]] in 2017 with approximately 5000 participants. }} {{clear left}}
